newsitem.title: USA: CBOT soy products end lower on late break in wheat.
newsitem.headline: CBOT soy products end lower on late break in wheat.

text.p: A late and quick drop from the day's highs in the CBOT wheat pit triggered local selling and day-trade profit taking in the soy commplex, traders said.
Soyoil and soymeal closed lower after trading higher much of the day on fresh bullish input from the domestic scene, they said.
Soymeal had found a supportive peg from cattle, specifically from Friday's USDA Seven State Cattle-On-Feed Report, traders said.
USDA said there were 8.544 million head of cattle on feed as of November 1, up one percent from a year ago.

The tally had been expected to drop 0.5 percent. The number of cattle placed on feed during November was 2.531 million, up 11 percent from a year ago, compared with expectations for a 5.7 percent rise.
Technicians cited bull flags from the four- and 20-day moving averages in the soy complex for the nearby December contracts.
Soymeal closed $0.80 to $2.00 per ton lower, with December down $0.80 at $236.90. Soyoil was 0.05 to 0.15 cent per lb lower, with December down 0.11 at 23.31.
